## External HTTP / API Calls (`infrastructure/http/*.client.ts`)

Any call to an external HTTP service (REST API, SOAP, GraphQL) is infrastructure. The domain defines **what** it needs via a port interface; the HTTP client implements **how** to get it.

**Structure:**
```
infrastructure/
└── http/
    └── exchange-rate/
        ├── exchange-rate.client.ts    ← implements IExchangeRatePort
        └── exchange-rate.client.spec.ts
```

**Rules:**
- Implements a domain port interface (`IXxxPort`) — never exposes HTTP-specific types to callers.
- Handles all transport concerns here: auth headers, retries, timeout, response parsing, error mapping.
- Maps HTTP errors to domain `BusinessError` subclasses before throwing — the application layer must never catch raw HTTP errors.
- Never inject an HTTP client into the domain or application layer directly — always go through the port.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD
@Injectable()
export class ExchangeRateHttpClient implements IExchangeRatePort {
  constructor(private readonly httpService: HttpService) {}

  async getRate(from: string, to: string, date: Date): Promise<number> {
    try {
      const { data } = await this.httpService.axiosRef.get('/rates', {
        params: { from, to, date: date.toISOString().slice(0, 10) },
        timeout: 5000,
      });
      return data.rate;
    } catch (e) {
      // Map transport error → domain error before it leaves infrastructure
      if (e.response?.status === 404)
        throw new ExchangeRateNotFoundError(from, to, date);
      throw new ExternalServiceUnavailableError('exchange-rate', e.message);
    }
  }
}

// ❌ BAD — HTTP client injected directly into application layer
@Injectable()
export class PricingService {
  constructor(private readonly httpService: HttpService) {} // ← leaks infrastructure
}
```

