## Query Efficiency — Mandatory Rules

Infrastructure must use the **minimum possible number of queries and API calls**. Every design decision in `infrastructure/` must be evaluated against this constraint.

### N+1 is always wrong

Never loop over IDs or keys and fire individual queries inside a `Promise.all` or `for` loop:

```ts
// ❌ NEVER — fires N separate SELECT statements
const results = await Promise.all(ids.map((id) => this.repo.findById(id)));

// ❌ NEVER — same problem with external API calls
const results = await Promise.all(subs.map((sub) => this.repo.findByIdPSub(sub)));
```

### Batch methods at every layer

When a port interface (`IUserLookupPort`, etc.) needs to resolve multiple entities by ID or key, the **repository interface** must expose a dedicated batch method. The port adapter then delegates to that single batch call:

```ts
// ✅ Domain interface — batch contract
export interface IUserRepository extends IRepository<User, string, UserFilter> {
  findByIds(ids: string[]): Promise<User[]>;
  findByIdPSubs(subs: string[]): Promise<User[]>;
}

// ✅ Infrastructure — single query, not a loop
async findByIds(ids: string[]): Promise<User[]> {
  if (ids.length === 0) return [];
  const rows = await this.delegate.findMany({
    where: { id: { in: ids }, deletedAt: null },
    include: INCLUDE_CHILDREN,
  });
  return (rows as UserProfileRow[]).map((r) => this.toDomain(r));
}

// ✅ Port adapter — one delegation, zero loops
async findByIds(ids: string[]): Promise<UserInfo[]> {
  const users = await this.repo.findByIds(ids);
  return users.map((u) => this.toUserInfo(u));
}
```

### Rules

| Scenario | Rule |
|---|---|
| Resolve many entities by ID | Add `findByIds` to repo interface; use `{ id: { in: ids } }` in Prisma |
| Resolve many entities by alternate key | Add `findByXxxs` to repo interface; use `{ xxx: { in: values } }` |
| Resolve many records via external API | Port must expose a batch method; HTTP client must use bulk endpoint if available |
| Early-exit on empty input | Always guard with `if (ids.length === 0) return [];` — avoids unnecessary DB round-trips |
| Ordered results required | Sort the result array in the adapter after the single query if DB ordering is insufficient |

